Step 2:

Perform a filter operation on dataframe, to get data sets of China and Asia, where I come from:

country_data <- gapminder %>% 
            filter(country == "China") 

continent_data <- gapminder %>% 
            filter(continent == "Asia")

Question:

Given these trends, what can you say about life expectancy since 1952? Again, don’t just say what’s happening in the graph. Tell some sort of story and speculate about the differences in the patterns.

Life expectancy for all continents is generally rising since 1952. It is perhaps because over the years, GDP per capita for most countries are rising (refer to graph below). A higher income offers access to better nutrition and healthcare, which in turn improve longevity. The increases in life expectancy for most countries are slowing down though. This may be because there is only a limit to which lifespan may increase. And higher living standards could lead to wealth-related problems such as obesity and cardiovascular diseases, that adversely impact one’s health. Some African countries experienced declines likely due to civil wars that destroy lives prematurely.

ggplot(data = gapminder , mapping = aes(x = year, y = gdpPercap, colour= country))+
geom_point() + 
geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
facet_wrap(~continent) +
theme(legend.position="none") + 
NULL

Data: Brexit Election Results
Data Structure: 632 rows of parliament constituency by 11 columns of constituency attributes (including % votes cast in favour of Brexit, % residents born in the UK, male ratio, unemployment rate, etc.)
Creator: Elliott Morris
Available from: DataCamp class on analysing election and polling data in R

Step 2:

Plot a histogram and a density plot of the leave share in all constituencies

ggplot(brexit_results, aes(x = leave_share)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 2.5) + 
  labs(title = "Spread of Vote Results (Discrete)",
       x = "% of people who voted leave",
       y = "number of constituencies")

ggplot(brexit_results, aes(x = leave_share)) +
  geom_density() + 
  labs(title = "Spread of Vote Results (Continuous)",
       x = "% of people who voted leave",
       y = "density")

Step 3:

Check the relationship (or correlation) between the proportion of native born residents (born_in_uk) in a constituency and its leave_share

brexit_results %>% 
  select(leave_share, born_in_uk) %>% 
  cor()
##             leave_share born_in_uk
## leave_share   1.0000000  0.4934295
## born_in_uk    0.4934295  1.0000000

The correlation is almost 0.5, which shows that the two variables are positively correlated.

Step 4:

Visualize the correlation, by creating a scatterplot between these two variables using geom_point. Add the best fit line, using geom_smooth(method = "lm").

Step 5:

Add labs() function to add an informative title, subtitle, and axes titles to all plots.

ggplot(brexit_results, aes(x = born_in_uk, y = leave_share)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.3) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  labs(title = "Relationship between Birth Place and Brexit Vote Preference",
       x = "% of people born in the uk",
       y = "% of people who voted leave") + 
  theme_bw() +
  NULL
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Question:

What can you say about the relationship shown above? Again, don’t just say what’s happening in the graph. Tell some sort of story and speculate about the differences in the patterns.

The scatters show a general upward trend, meaning that the higher proportion of native born voters, the more likely votes in favor of leave prevail. This observation could indicate that native born voters prefer a non-Europe identity. There are also significant segments where a large proportion is native and yet they prefer to stay in the EU. They perhaps welcome diversity and value the benefits of the EU over the costs. The best-fit line shows a positive correlation, confirming the general observation.
